"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 1 Subtracting Mixed Numbers with Regrouping, Part 1 Power Up Building Power facts Power Up G mental math a. Calculation: 8 × 25 b. Number Sense: 630 − 50 c. Number Sense: 62 + 19 d. Money: $4.50 + 75¢ e. Fractional Parts: 1 2 of $15.00 f. Money: $25.00 g. Geometry: What is the relationship between the radius and the diameter of a circle? h. Calculation: 4 × 7, − 1, ÷ 3, × 4, ÷ 6, × 3, ÷ 2 problem solving Josepha is making sack lunches. She has two kinds of sandwiches, three kinds of fruit, and two kinds of juice. If each sack lunch contains one kind of sandwich, one kind of fruit, and one kind of juice, how many different sack-lunch combinations can Josepha make? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Here is another “separating” problem about pies: There were 4 1 6 pies on the restaurant shelf. The server sliced one of the whole pies into sixths. Then the server removed 1 2 6 pies. How many pies were left on the shelf? Thinking Skill Discuss What words or phrases in the problem give clues about which operation we should use to answer the question? We may illustrate this problem with circles. There were 4 1 6 pies on the shelf. 4 1 The server sliced one of the whole pies into sixths. This makes 3 7 6 pies, which equals 4 1 6 pies. 3 7"
"Then the server removed 12 6 pies. So 25 6 pies were left on the shelf. Now we show the arithmetic for subtracting 12 6 from 41 6. 6 pies − 12 6 pies Thinking Skill Verify How can you check the answer to the subtraction problem? We cannot subtract 2 6 from 1 6, so we rename 41 6. Just as the server sliced one of the pies into sixths, so we change one of the four wholes into 6 6. This makes three whole pies plus 6 6 plus 1 6, which is 37 6. Now we can subtract. 3  6 6  1 − 12 6 pies − 12 6 pies 6 pies Example Subtract: 51 3  22 Solution We cannot subtract 2 3 from 1 3, so we rename 51 3. We change one of the five wholes into 3 3. Then we combine 4 and 3 3  1 3 to get 44 3. Now we can subtract. 4  3 3  1  22  22 Practice Set Subtract. a. 1 2 4 1 b. 2 3 3 2 c. 1 3 5 2 d. 2 4 5 1 e. 4 10 7 3 f. 2 3 6 1 3 7"
