"L E S S O N Common Denominators, Part 2 Power Up Building Power facts Power Up G mental math a. Number Sense: 8 × 250 b. Number Sense: 462 − 350 c. Number Sense: 150 + 49 d. Money: $3.75 + $4.50 e. Fractional Parts: 1 2 of 15 f. Number Sense: 30 × 40 g. Measurement: How many centimeters are in 10 meters? h. Calculation: 10 × 8, + 1, ÷ 9, × 3, + 1, ÷ 4, × 6, − 2, ÷ 5 problem solving Terry folded a square piece of paper in half diagonally to form a triangle. Then he folded the triangle in half as shown, making a smaller triangle. With scissors Terry cut off the upper corner of the triangle. What will the paper look like when it is unfolded? New Concept Increasing Knowledge In Lesson 55 we added and subtracted fractions that did not have common denominators. We renamed one of the fractions in order to add or subtract. In this lesson we will rename both fractions before we add or subtract. To see why this is sometimes necessary, consider the problem below. Tony and Catherine ordered a pineapple pizza. Tony ate half and Catherine ate a third. What fraction of the pizza did Tony and Catherine eat? We cannot add the fractions 1 2 and 1 3 by simply counting the number of parts, because the parts are not the same size (that is, the denominators are different). These fractions do not have common denominators. "
"Saxon Math Course 1 Thinking Skill Explain How do you rename a fraction? Renaming 1 2 as 2 4 does not help us either. In the fractions 2 4 and 1 3, the parts are still of different sizes. These fractions do not have common denominators. We must rename both fractions in order to get parts that are the same size. The least common multiple of the denominators can be used as the common denominator of the renamed fractions. The least common multiple of 2 and 3 (the denominators of 1 2 and 1 3 ) is 6. 6 1 6 1 2 = 3 = The common denominator is 6. Example 1 Add: 1 2 1 Solution The denominators are 2 and 3. The least common multiple of 2 and 3 is 6. We rename each fraction so that 6 is the common denominator. Then we add. Rename 1 2 and 1 3. 1 3 2 2 2 2 3 3 3 Example 2 Risa saw that she had 3 4 of a carton of 12 eggs. She used 2 3 of a whole carton to make a batch of French toast for the family. What fraction of a carton of eggs was not used? Solution To find the fraction that remains, we subtract 2 3 from 3 4. The least common multiple of 4 and 3 is 12. We rename both fractions so that their denominators are 12 and then subtract. Then add."
"Rename 3 4 and 2 3. 2 3 4 4 8 4 3 3 9 We can check for reasonableness by thinking about the number of eggs. If the carton holds 12 eggs, then there were nine eggs in the carton because 4 of 12 is 9. Risa used 2 3 of 12 eggs, which is 8 eggs. Subtracting 8 from 9 leaves 1 egg in the carton, which is 1 12 of a carton. Renaming one or more fractions can also help us compare fractions. To compare fractions that have common denominators, we simply compare the numerators. 6 6 5 To compare fractions that do not have common denominators, we can rename one or both fractions so that they do have common denominators. Example 3 Compare: 3 Solution We rename 1 2 so that the denominator is 8. 2 4 4 4 We see that 3 8 is less than 4 8. 8 6 4 Therefore, 3 8 is less than 1 2. 8 1 The answer is reasonable because the numerator of 3 8, which is 3, is less than half of the denominator 8, indicating that the fraction is less than 1 2. Example 4 Compare: 2 Solution The denominators are 3 and 4. We rename both fractions with a common denominator of 12. 3 4 4 8 4 3 3 9 We see that 8 12 is less than 9 12. Then subtract."
