"24. (38) Analyze The area of a square is 16 square inches. What is its perimeter? * 25. (60) This figure shows the shape of home plate on a baseball field. What kind of a polygon is shown? 26. (41) Explain The sales-tax rate was 7%. Dexter bought two items, one for $4.95 and the other for $2.79. What was the total cost of the two items including sales tax? Describe how to use estimation to check whether your answer is reasonable. 27. (52) Ramla bought a sheet of 100 stamps from the post office for $39. What was the price of each stamp? * 28. (Inv. 6) Represent Draw a rectangular prism. A rectangular prism has how many a. faces? b. edges? c. vertices? Refer to the cube shown below to answer problems 29 and 30. * 29. (Inv. 6) Each face of a cube is a square. What is the area of each face of this cube? * 30. (Inv. 6) Find the total surface area of the cube by adding up the area of all of the faces of the cube. Early Finishers Math and Architecture The Pentagon in Washington, D.C. is the world’s largest office building. Each of the five sides of the Pentagon is 921 feet long. What is the perimeter of the Pentagon in yards? 3 cm"
"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 1 Writing Mixed Numbers as Improper Fractions Power Up Building Power facts Power Up G mental math a. Number Sense: 5 × 40 b. Number Sense: 475 + 1200 c. Calculation: 3 × 84 d. Calculation: $8.50 + $2.50 e. Fractional Parts: 1 3 of $36.00 f. Number Sense: $25 g. Measurement: Convert 240 seconds into minutes. h. Calculation: 6 × 8, − 4, ÷ 4, × 2, + 2, ÷ 6, ÷ 2 problem solving There are approximately 520 nine-inch long noodles in a 1-pound package of spaghetti. Placed end-to-end, how many feet of noodles are in a pound of uncooked spaghetti? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Here is another word problem about pies. In this problem we will change a mixed number to an improper fraction. There were 35 6 pies on the shelf. The restaurant manager asked the server to cut the whole pies into sixths. Altogether, how many slices of pie were there after the server cut the pies? We illustrate this problem with circles. There were 3 5 6 pies on the shelf. The server cut the whole pies into sixths. Each whole pie then had six slices. Thinking Skill Model Use your fraction manipulatives to represent 3 5 6."
"The three whole pies contain 18 slices (3 × 6 = 18). The 5 additional slices from the 5 6 of a pie bring the total to 23 slices (23 sixths). This problem illustrates that 35 6 is equivalent to 23 6 . Now we describe the arithmetic for changing a mixed number such as 35 6 to an improper fraction. Recall that a mixed number has a whole-number part and a fraction part. whole number fraction The denominator of the mixed number will also be the denominator of the improper fraction. 6  6 same denominator The denominator indicates the size of the fraction “pieces.” In this case the fraction pieces are sixths, so we change the whole number 3 into sixths. We know that one whole is 6 6, so three wholes is 3 × 6 6, which is 18 6 . Therefore, we add 18 6 and 5 6 to get 23 6 . 6  5 6  23 6  6 6  6 6  5 6  23 Example 1 Write 2 3 4 as an improper fraction. Solution The denominator of the fraction part of the mixed number is fourths, so the denominator of the improper fraction will also be fourths. 2 3 4 4 We change the whole number 2 into fourths. Since 1 equals 4 4, the whole number 2 equals 2 × 4 4, which is 8 4. We add 8 4 and 3 4 to get 11 4 . 4 3 4 11 2 3 Represent Draw a model to show that 2 3 4 = 11 4 ."
"Saxon Math Course 1 Example 2 Write 5 2 3 as an improper fraction. Solution We see that the denominator of the improper fraction will be thirds. 5 2 3 3 Some people use a quick, mechanical method to find the numerator of the improper fraction. Looking at the mixed number, they multiply the denominator by the whole number and then add the numerator. The result is the numerator of the improper fraction. 5 2 3  17 Example 3 Write 1 2 3 and 2 2 5 as improper fractions. Then multiply the improper fractions. What is the product? Solution First we write 1 2 3 and 2 2 5 as improper fractions. 1 2 3 2 3 5 2 2 5 2 5 12 Next we multiply 5 3 by 12 5 . 3 12 5  60 The result is an improper fraction, which we simplify. 15  4 So 12 3  22 5 equals 4. Practice Set Write each mixed number as an improper fraction: a. 24 b. 3 1 c. 13 d. 61 e. 15 f. 3 3 g. 21 h. 121 i. 31 j. Write 11 2 and 3 1 3 as improper fractions. Then multiply the improper fractions. What is the product? Thinking Skill Evaluate Which method of changing a mixed number to an improper fraction do you prefer, the method in example 1 or example 2? Why?"
"Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (54) In music there are whole notes, half notes, quarter notes, and eighth notes. a. How many quarter notes equal a whole note? b. How many eighth notes equal a quarter note? * 2. (62) Don is 5 feet 21 2 inches tall. How many inches tall is that? 3. (19) Classify Which of these numbers is not a prime number? A 11 B 21 C 31 D 41 * 4. (62) Analyze Write 11 3 and 11 2 as improper fractions, and multiply the improper fractions. What is the product? 5. (58) If the chance of rain is 20%, what is the chance that it will not rain? 6. (18) The prices for three pairs of skates were $36.25, $41.50, and $43.75. What was the average price for a pair of skates? Estimate to show that your answer is reasonable. 7. (43) Evaluate Instead of dividing 15 by 21 2, Solomon doubled both numbers and then divided mentally. What was Solomon’s mental division problem and its quotient? Find each unknown number: * 8. (43, 59) m 4 3 8 3 1 9. (43, 56) n 3 10 3 10. (43, 45) 6d = 0.456 11. (43, 49) 0.04w = 1.5 * 12. (61) 2 3 4 5 * 13. (57) 6 1 14. (29) 2 4 15. (54) 3 1 16. (40) 1 − (0.2 − 0.03) 17. (39) (0.14)(0.16) 18. (49) One centimeter equals 10 millimeters. How many millimeters does 2.5 centimeters equal? 19. (19) List all of the common factors of 18 and 24. Then circle the greatest common factor. * 20. (58) Analyze Ten marbles are in a bag. Four of the marbles are red. a. If one marble is drawn from the bag, what is the probability that it will be red? b. Write the complement of the event in a and state its probability. c. Describe the relationship between the event and its complement. 21. (38) Analyze If the perimeter of a square is 40 mm, what is the area of the square?"
"Saxon Math Course 1 22. (14) At 6 a.m. the temperature was −6°F. At noon the temperature was 14°F. From 6 a.m. to noon the temperature rose how many degrees? 23. (47) Lisa used a compass to draw a circle with a radius of 11 2 inches. a. What was the diameter of the circle? b. What was the circumference of the circle? (Use 3.14 for π.) The circle graph below shows the favorite sport of 100 people. Refer to the graph to answer problems 24–27. Favorite Sport of 100 People Baseball Other Football Basketball 24. (40) How many more people favored baseball than favored football? 25. (40) What fraction of the people surveyed favored baseball? 26. (40) Explain Was any sport the favorite sport of the majority of the people surveyed? Write one or two sentences to explain your answer. 27. (40) Connect Since baseball was the favorite sport of 40 out of 100 people, it was the favorite sport of 40% of the people surveyed. What percent of the people answered that football was their favorite sport? 28. (41) What number is 40% of 200? 29. (19) Here we show 18 written as a product of prime numbers: 2 ∙ 3 ∙ 3 Write 20 as a product of prime numbers. * 30. (Inv. 5) Analyze Judges awarded Sandra these scores for her performance on the vault: 9.1, 8.9, 9.0, 9.2, 9.2 What is the median score?"
"L E S S O N Subtracting Mixed Numbers with Regrouping, Part 2 Power Up Building Power facts Power Up D mental math a. Number Sense: 5 × 140 b. Number Sense: 420 − 50 c. Calculation: 4 × 63 d. Calculation: $8.50 − $2.50 e. Number Sense: Double 7 1 2. f. Number Sense: $25 g. Measurement: How many inches are in 6 feet? h. Calculation: 5 × 10, − 20, + 2, ÷ 4, + 1, ÷ 3, − 3 problem solving Rhett chooses a marble at random from each of the four boxes below. From which box is he most likely to choose a blue marble? A B C D New Concept Increasing Knowledge Since Lesson 48 we have practiced subtracting mixed numbers with regrouping. In this lesson we will rename the fractions with common denominators before subtracting. To subtract 1 1 2 from 3 2 3, we first rewrite the fractions with common denominators. Then we subtract the whole numbers and the fractions. If possible, we simplify. 2 1 1 1 2 3 3 1 3 3 2 3 2 2 3 4 When subtracting, it is sometimes necessary to regroup. We rewrite the fractions with common denominators before regrouping."
"Saxon Math Course 1 Example Subtract: 5 1 2 1 2 Solution Thinking Skill Explain Explain Why did we regroup in this example but not in the previous problem? We rewrite the fractions with common denominators. Before we can subtract, we must regroup. After we subtract, we simplify if possible. Justify Why can we use addition to check the answer? Practice Set Subtract: a. 5 1 2 3 1 b. 4 1 4 2 1 c. 6 1 2 1 3 d. 7 2 3 3 5 e. 6 1 6 1 1 f. 4 1 3 1 1 g. 4 5 6 1 1 h. 6 1 2 3 5 i. 8 2 3 5 3 j. Formulate Write a word problem that involves subtracting mixed numbers. Written Practice Strengthening Concepts * 1. (12, 53) Connect What is the difference between the sum of 0.6 and 0.4 and the product of 0.6 and 0.4? * 2. (14) Analyze Mt. Whitney, the highest point in California, has an elevation of 14,494 feet above sea level. From there one can see Death Valley, which contains the lowest point in California, 282 feet below sea level. The floor of Death Valley is how many feet below the peak of Mt. Whitney? * 3. (10) Conclude It was 39° outside at 1 p.m. By 7 p.m. the temperature had dropped 11° and was below freezing. What was the temperature at 7 p.m.? On what scale is the temperature being measured? * 4. (62) Write the mixed number 4 2 3 as an improper fraction. * 5. (62) Explain Round $678.25 to the nearest ten dollars. Describe how you decided upon your answer. 6. (32) Explain What time is 2 1 2 hours after 10:15 a.m.? How did you find your answer? 7. (5) (30 × 15) ÷ (30 − 15) 8. (56) Compare: 5 8 2 9. (43) w 3 2 3 1 1 10. (55) 8 3 3 5 1 2 3 2 2 1 4 5 1 2 3 3 5"
"* 11. (63) 6 1 4 5 5 12. (29) 4 2 13. (54) 4 2 14. (53) (1 − 0.4)(1 + 0.4) 15. (41) How much money is 60% of $45? 16. (45) 0.4 ÷ 8 17. (49) 8 ÷ 0.4 18. (10) Predict What is the next number in this sequence? 0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8, … 19. (19) What is the tenth prime number? * 20. (8, 59) What is the perimeter of this rectangle? 4 in. 8 in. * 21. (Inv. 6) A triangular prism has how many a. faces? b. edges? c. vertices? 22. (16) Write 2 1 2 and 1 1 5 as improper fractions. Then multiply the improper fractions and simplify the product. 23. (31) This rectangle is divided into two congruent regions. What is the area of the shaded region? * 24. (15, 62) A ton is 2000 pounds. How many pounds is 2 1 2 tons? 25. (50) Connect Which arrow could be pointing to 0.2 on this number line? –1 –2 A B C D 26. (47) Evaluate The paper cup would not roll straight. One end was 7 cm in diameter, and the other end was 5 cm in diameter. In one roll of the cup, a. how far would the larger end roll? b. how far would the smaller end roll? (Round each answer to the nearest centimeter. Use 3.14 for π.) 30 cm 10 cm"
"Saxon Math Course 1 27. (29, 33) Jefferson got a hit 30% of the 240 times he went to bat during the season. Write 30% as a reduced fraction. Then find the number of hits Jefferson got during the season. 28. (43) Jena has run 11.5 miles of a 26.2-mile race. Find the remaining distance Jena has to run by solving this equation: 11.5 mi + d = 26.2 mi 29. (41) The sales-tax rate was 7%. The two CDs cost $15.49 each. What was the total cost of the two CDs including tax? * 30. (57) Rosa is mixing paint in ceramics class. She mixes 1 2 teaspoon of yellow paint with 3 4 teaspoon of red paint to make orange paint. How much orange paint does Rosa make? Early Finishers Real-World Application The drama club had their first annual meeting this afternoon. The officers had decided to order pizza for all the new members this year. They ordered one cheese, one mushroom, and one tomato pizza. Due to the rain, the turnout for the meeting was small and there was a lot of pizza left. They had 1 4 of the cheese pizza, 1 2 of the mushroom pizza and 5 12 of the tomato pizza left. How much leftover pizza did the drama club have?"
"L E S S O N Classifying Quadrilaterals Power Up Building Power facts Power Up J mental math a. Number Sense: 5 × 240 b. Number Sense: 4500 + 450 c. Calculation: 7 × 34 d. Calculation: $7.50 + $7.50 e. Fractional Parts: 1 4 of $20.00 f. Number Sense: $75 g. Measurement: How many meters are in 200 centimeters? h. Calculation: 6 × 8, ÷ 2, + 1, ÷ 5, – 1, × 4, ÷ 2 problem solving Emily has a blue folder, a green folder, and a red folder. She uses one folder each for her math, science, and history classes. She does not use her blue folder for math. Her green folder is not used for science. She does not use her red folder for history. If her red folder is not used for math, what folder does Emily use for each subject? Make a table to show your work. New Concept Increasing Knowledge Math Language The prefix quadri- means four. A quadrilateral is a polygon with four sides. We learned in Lesson 60 that quadrilaterals are polygons with four sides. We can classify (sort) quadrilaterals by the characteristics of their sides and angles. The following table describes the various classifications of quadrilaterals: No sides parallel One pair of parallel sides Two pairs of parallel sides Parallelogram with equal sides Parallelogram with right angles Rectangle with equal sides Trapezium Trapezoid Parallelogram Rhombus Rectangle Square Shape Characteristic Name Classifications of Quadrilaterals"
"Saxon Math Course 1 Notice that squares, rectangles, and rhombuses are all parallelograms. Also notice that a square is a special kind of rectangle, which is a special kind of parallelogram, which is a special kind of quadrilateral, which is a special kind of polygon. A square is also a special kind of rhombus. Example 1 Is the following statement true or false? All parallelograms are rectangles. Solution Thinking Skill Justify How can we rewrite the statement in example 1 so that it is true? We are asked to decide whether every parallelogram is a rectangle. Since a rectangle is a special kind of parallelogram, some parallelograms are rectangles. However, some parallelograms are not rectangles. Since not all parallelograms are rectangles, the statement is false. Example 2 Draw a pair of parallel lines. Then draw another pair of parallel lines. These lines should intersect the first pair but not be perpendicular to the first pair. What is the name for the quadrilateral that is formed by the intersecting lines? Solution We draw the first pair of parallel lines. We draw the second pair of lines so that the lines are not perpendicular to the first pair. At right we have colored the segments that form the quadrilateral. The quadrilateral formed is a parallelogram. Practice Set a. What is a quadrilateral? b. Describe the difference between a parallelogram and a trapezoid. c. Model Draw a rhombus that is a square. d. Model Draw a rhombus that is not a square. e. Verify True or false: Some rectangles are squares. f. Verify True or false: All squares are rectangles. Written Practice Strengthening Concepts * 1. (12, 53) When the sum of 1.3 and 1.2 is divided by the difference of 1.3 and 1.2, what is the quotient? 2. (13) William Shakespeare was born in 1564 and died in 1616. How many years did he live?"
"3. (15) Duane kicked a 45-yard field goal. How many feet is 45 yards? * 4. (60) Explain Why is a square a regular quadrilateral? * 5. (60) A regular hexagon has a perimeter of 36 inches. How long is each side? 6. (42) 4  ? 7. (5) 8 8 8 8 * 8. (59) 5 2 3 3 3 * 9. (61) 2 2 3 1 10. (57) 10 1 * 11. (63) 6 1 2 2 7 12. (44) Compare: 2 × 0.4 2 + 0.4 13. (39) 4.8 × 0.35 14. (49) 1 ÷ 0.4 15. (15) How many $0.12 pencils can Mr. Velazquez buy for $4.80? 16. (51) Estimate Round the product of 0.33 and 0.38 to the nearest hundredth. 17. (31) Multiply the length by the width to find the area of this rectangle. * 18. (64) Conclude Is every rectangle a parallelogram? 19. (19) Analyze What is the twelfth prime number? 20. (38) The area of a square is 9 cm2. a. How long is each side of the square? b. What is the perimeter of the square? Refer to the box shown below to answer problems 21 and 22. * 21. (Inv. 6) This box has how many faces? Draw a net to show how the box would look if you cut it apart and flattened it. * 22. (Inv. 6) If this box is a cube and each edge is 10 inches long, then a. what is the area of each face? b. what is the total surface area of the cube? 23. (15) There are 100 centimeters in a meter. How many centimeters equal 2.5 meters? * 24. (62) Write the mixed numbers 1 1 2 and 2 1 2 as improper fractions. Then multiply the improper fractions and simplify the product. 2 in. 4 in."
