"* 19. (65) Use division by primes to find the prime factorization of 50. * 20. (60) Connect What is the name of a six-sided polygon? How many vertices does it have? * 21. (62) Write 3 4 7 as an improper fraction. 22. (38) The area of a square is 36 square inches. a. What is the length of each side? b. What is the perimeter of the square? 23. (33) Write 16% as a reduced fraction. 24. (7) How many millimeters long is the line segment below? cm 25. (7) Estimate A meter is about 1 1 10 yards. About how many meters long is an automobile? * 26. (65) Write the prime factorization of 375 and of 1000. What method did you use? 27. (54) Reduce: 3 5 5 5 2 2 2 5 5 5 28. (47) Estimate The radius of the carousel is 15 feet. If the carousel turns around once, a person riding on the outer edge will travel how far? Round the answer to the nearest foot. (Use 3.14 for π.) Describe how to mentally check whether the answer is reasonable. 29. (29, 33) Eighty percent of the 20 answers were correct. How many answers were correct? 30. (54) Verify The prefix “rect-” in rectangle means “right.” A rectangle is a “right-angle” shape. Why is every square also a rectangle?"
"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 1 Multiplying Mixed Numbers Power Up Building Power facts Power Up J mental math a. Number Sense: 5 × 160 b. Number Sense: 376 + 99 c. Calculation: 8 × 23 d. Calculation: $1.75 + $1.75 e. Fractional Parts: 1 3 of $60.00 f. Number Sense: $30 g. Measurement: Which is greater, 5 years or a decade? h. Calculation: 8 × 8, − 4, ÷ 2, + 3, ÷ 3, + 1, ÷ 6, ÷ 2 problem solving In this figure a square and a regular pentagon share a common side. The area of the square is 25 square centimeters. What is the perimeter of the pentagon? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Recall from Lesson 57 the three steps to solving an arithmetic problem with fractions. Step 1: Put the problem into the correct shape (if it is not already). Step 2: Perform the operation indicated. Step 3: Simplify the answer if possible. Remember that putting fractions into the correct shape for adding and subtracting means writing the fractions with common denominators. To multiply or divide fractions, we do not need to use common denominators. However, we must write the fractions in fraction form. This means we will write mixed numbers and whole numbers as improper fractions. We write a whole number as an improper fraction by making the whole number the numerator of a fraction with a denominator of 1. Example 1 A length of fabric was cut into 4 equal sections. Each of 4 students received 2 2 3 yd of fabric. How much fabric was there before it was cut? Thinking Skill Verify How do we write a mixed number as a fraction?"
"Solution This is an equal groups problem. To find the original length of the fabric we multiply 2 2 3 yd by 4. First, we write 2 2 3 and 4 in fraction form. 3 4 Second, we multiply the numerators to find the numerator of the product, and we multiply the denominators to find the denominator of the product. 3 4 1 32 Third, we simplify the product by converting the improper fraction to a mixed number. 3 10 2 Before the fabric was cut it was 10 2 3 yd long. Evaluate How can we use estimation to check whether our answer is reasonable? Example 2 Multiply: 2 1 2 1 1 Solution First, we write the numbers in fraction form. 2 4 Reading Math Recall that the terms of a fraction are the numerator and the denominator. Second, we multiply the terms of the fractions. 2 4 3 20 Third, we simplify the product. 6 3 2 6 3 1 Sketching a rectangle on a grid is a way to check the reasonableness of a product of mixed numbers. To illustrate the product of 2 1 2 and 3 1 2, we use a grid that is at least 3 by 4 so that a 2 1 2 by 3 1 2 rectangle fits on the grid. We sketch the rectangle and estimate the area. There are 6 full squares, 5 half squares, and a quarter square. Since 2 half squares equal a whole square, the area is about 8 3 4 square units."
"Saxon Math Course 1 Practice Set Multiply: a. 1 1 2 2 b. 1 2 3 3 c. 1 1 2 1 2 d. 1 2 3 3 e. 2 1 2 2 2 f. 3 1 3 g. 3 1 3 1 2 h. 2 3 4 2 i. 2 3 1 j. Check the reasonableness of the products in e and h by sketching rectangles on a grid. k. Formulate Write and solve a word problem about multiplying a whole number and a mixed number. Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (29, 33) Fifty percent of the 60 questions on the test are multiple choice. Find the number of multiple-choice questions on the test. 2. (58) Analyze Twelve of the 30 students in the class are boys. a. What is the ratio of boys to girls in the class? b. If each student’s name is placed in a hat and one name is drawn, what is the probability that it will be the name of a girl? 3. (15) Analyze Some railroad rails weigh 155 pounds per yard. How much would a 33-foot-long rail weigh? * 4. (66) 1 1 2 2 2 * 5. (66) 2 2 3 2 6. (18) The sum of five numbers is 200. What is the average of the numbers? 7. (5) 100 75 100 75 8. (59) 1 1 5 3 1 * 9. (61) 3 1 6 1 * 10. (63) 35 1 4 12 1 11. (29) 5 1 12. (54) 5 1 13. (45) 0.25 ÷ 5 14. (49) 5 ÷ 0.25 15. (39) What is the product of the answers to problems 13 and 14? 16. (54) Verify Which of the following is equal to 1 2 1 2? A 1 2 1 B a1 2b C 1 2 1 * 17. (65) Represent Use a factor tree to find the prime factorization of 30. 18. (15) If three pencils cost a total of 75¢, how much would six pencils cost?"
"19. (41) Seven and one half percent is equivalent to the decimal number 0.075. If the sales-tax rate is 7 1 2%, what is the sales tax on a $10.00 purchase? * 20. (60) Analyze One side of a regular pentagon measures 0.8 meter. What is the perimeter of the regular pentagon? 21. (29) Twenty minutes is what fraction of an hour? 22. (14) The temperature dropped from 12°C to −8°C. This was a drop of how many degrees? The bar graph below shows the weights of different types of cereals packaged in the same size boxes. Refer to the graph to answer problems 23–25. Fruit and Flakes Flakes Type of Cereal Weight of Cereal Weight (in ounces) Puffed 23. (Inv. 5) What is the range of the weights? 24. (Inv. 5) What is the mean weight of the three types of cereal? * 25. (13) Formulate Write a comparison word problem that relates to the graph, and then answer the problem. * 26. (65) Connect Use division by primes to find the prime factorization of 400. 27. (38) Analyze Simon covered the floor of a square room with 144 square floor tiles. How many floor tiles were along each wall of the room? 28. (46) Estimate The weight of a 1-kilogram object is about 2.2 pounds. A large man may weigh 100 kilograms. About how many pounds is that? 29. (54) Reduce: 5 5 5 7 2 2 2 5 5 5 * 30. (60) Classify Which of these polygons is not a regular polygon? A B C D"
"L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 1 Using Prime Factorization to Reduce Fractions Power Up Building Power facts Power Up J mental math a. Number Sense: 5 × 260 b. Number Sense: 341 − 50 c. Calculation: 3 × 48 d. Calculation: $9.25 − 75¢ e. Number Sense: Double $1.25. f. Number Sense: $30 g. Measurement: Which is greater, 3 yards or 5 feet? h. Calculation: 6 × 6, − 1, ÷ 5, × 2, + 1, ÷ 3, ÷ 2 problem solving Copy this problem and fill in the missing digits: New Concept Increasing Knowledge One way to reduce fractions with large terms is to factor the terms and then reduce the common factors. To reduce 125 1000, we could begin by writing the prime factorizations of 125 and 1000. 1000  5 5 5 2 2 2 5 5 5 Thinking Skill Explain What are two strategies for finding the prime factorization of a number? We see three pairs of 5 s that can be reduced. Each 5 5 reduces to 1 1. 5 5 2 2 2 5 1 5 1 5 1 We multiply the remaining factors and find that 125 1000 reduces to 1 8. Example Reduce: 375 Solution Thinking Skill Discuss When is it helpful to use prime factorization to reduce a fraction? We write the prime factorization of both the numerator and the denominator. 1000  3 5 5 5 2 2 2 5 5 5 = 3 5 5 5 2 2 2 5 1 5 1 5 3 Then we reduce the common factors and multiply the remaining factors. _ _ _,_ _ _ × 7 999,999"
