"L E S S O N Dividing Mixed Numbers Power Up Building Power facts Power Up I mental math a. Number Sense: 5 × 80 b. Number Sense: 275 + 1500 c. Calculation: 7 × 42 d. Calculation: $5.75 + 50¢ e. Fractional Parts: 1 4 of $48.00 f. Number Sense: $120 g. Measurement: Which is greater, 1 meter or 100 millimeters? h. Calculation: 7 × 8, – 1, ÷ 5, × 2, – 1, ÷ 3, − 8 problem solving Megan has many gray socks, white socks, and black socks in a drawer. In the dark she pulled out two socks that did not match. How many more socks does Megan need to pull from the drawer to be certain to have a matching pair? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Recall the three steps to solving an arithmetic problem with fractions. Step 1: Put the problem into the correct shape (if it is not already). Step 2: Perform the operation indicated. Step 3: Simplify the answer if possible. In this lesson we will practice dividing mixed numbers. Recall from Lesson 66 that the correct shape for multiplying and dividing fractions is fraction form. So when dividing, we first write any mixed numbers or whole numbers as improper fractions. Example 1 Shawna is pouring 2 2 3 cups of plant food into equal amounts to feed 4 plants. How much plant food is there for each plant?"
"Saxon Math Course 1 Solution Shawna is dividing 2 2 3 cups of plant food into four equal groups. We divide 2 2 by 4. We write the numbers as improper fractions. 3 4 Math Language Reciprocals are two numbers whose product is 1. To divide, we find the number of 4s in 1. ( That is, we find the reciprocal of 4.) Then we use the reciprocal of 4 to find the number of 4s in 8 3. 1 4 1 1 3 1 4 8 We simplify the answer. 12 2 There is 2 3 cup of plant food for each plant. Notice that dividing a number by 4 is equivalent to finding 1 4 of the number. Instead of dividing 2 2 3 by 4, we could have directly found 1 4 of 2 2 3. Example 2 Divide: 2 2 3 1 1 Solution Thinking Skill Justify Describe in your own words how to divide mixed numbers. We write the mixed numbers as improper fractions. 3 3 To divide, we find the number of 3 2 s in 1. ( That is, we find the reciprocal of 3 2.) Then we use the reciprocal of 3 2 to find the number of 3 2 s in 8 3. 3 2 3 16 1 3 2 2 We simplify the improper fraction 16 9 as shown below. 9 1 7 Practice Set Find each product or quotient: a. 1 3 5 4 b. 1 4 of 1 3 c. 2 2 5 3 d. 1 3 of 2 2 e. Generalize Why is dividing by 4 the same as multiplying by 1 4?"
"f. 1 2 3 2 1 g. 2 1 2 1 2 h. 1 1 2 1 1 i. 7 1 3 j. Gabriel has 2 1 4 hours to finish three projects. If he divides his time equally, what fraction of an hour can he spend on each project? Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (12, 55) What is the difference between the sum of 1 2 and 1 4 and the product of 1 and 1 4? 2. (15) Bill ran a half mile in two minutes fifty-five seconds. How many seconds is that? 3. (15) The gauge of a railroad—the distance between the two tracks—is usually 4 feet 8 1 2 inches. How many inches is that? * 4. (68) 1 1 2 2 2 * 5. (68) 1 1 3 4 6. (18) In six games Yvonne scored a total of 108 points. How many points per game did she average? * 7. (67) Write the prime factorizations of 24 and 200. Then reduce 24 200. Find each unknown number: * 8. (59) m 5 3 8 1 3 9. (59) 3 3 5 2 7 10 n 10. (45) 25d = 0.375 11. (42) 4 w * 12. (63) 5 1 8 1 1 * 13. (66) 3 1 3 1 1 * 14. (68) 3 1 3 1 1 15. (31, 66) What is the area of a rectangle that is 4 inches long and 1 3 4 inches wide? 16. (53) (3.2 + 1) − (0.6 × 7) 17. (49) 12.5 ÷ 0.4 * 18. (52) Analyze The product 3.2 × 10 equals which of the following? A 32 ÷ 10 B 320 ÷ 10 C 0.32 ÷ 10 19. (16) Estimate Find the sum of 6416, 5734, and 4912 to the nearest thousand. 20. (43) Verify Instead of dividing 800 by 24, Arturo formed an equivalent division problem by dividing both the dividend and the divisor by 8. Then he quickly found the quotient of the equivalent problem. What is the equivalent problem Arturo formed, and what is the quotient? Write the quotient as a mixed number."
