"* 25. (89) Estimate On this number line the arrow could be pointing to which of the following? A 21 B 22 C 23 D 24 * 26. (92) Write this number in standard notation: (7 × 109 ) + (2 × 108) + (5 × 107) 27. (58) a. What is the probability of rolling a 6 with a single roll of a number cube? b. What is the probability of rolling a number less than 6 with a single roll of a number cube? c. Name the event and its complement. Then describe the relationship between the two probabilities. 28. (64, Inv. 7) Represent The coordinates of the four vertices of a quadrilateral are (−3, −2), (0, 2), (3, 2), and (5, −2). What is the name for this type of quadrilateral? * 29. (91) Explain The formula for the area of a triangle is A bh If the base measures 20 cm and the height measures 15 cm, then what is the area of the triangle? Explain your thinking. 30. (10, 17) Generalize Write the rule for this sequence. Then write the next four numbers. 16, 1 8, 3 16, 1 4, 5 16, 3 8, , , , , . . . Early Finishers Real-World Application A teacher emptied a 1.5 oz snack-sized box of raisins into a dish. The teacher then asked for volunteers to estimate the number of raisins in the dish. Twelve volunteers gave the following estimates. 84 100 50 75 66 75 70 90 85 77 91 80 a. Which type of display—a circle graph or a stem-and-leaf plot—is the most appropriate way to display this data? Draw your display and justify your choice. b. The dish contained exactly 85 raisins. How many volunteers made a reasonable estimate? Give a reason to support your answer. (Hint: You might think of how far off an estimate is in terms of a percent of 85.)"
"Writing Fractions and Decimals as Percents, Part 2 Power Up Building Power facts Power Up K mental math a. Number Sense: 50 ∙70 b. Number Sense: 572 + 150 c. Percent: 50% of 80 d. Calculation: $10.00 − $6.36 e. Decimals: 100 × 0.02 f. Number Sense: 640 g. Algebra: If r = 6, what does 9r equal? h. Calculation: 4 × 5, + 1, ÷ 3, × 8, − 1, ÷ 5, × 4, − 2, ÷ 2 problem solving What are the next four numbers in this sequence: 1 12, 1 6, 1 4, 1 3, . . . New Concept Increasing Knowledge Since Lesson 75 we have practiced changing a fraction or decimal to a percent by writing an equivalent fraction with a denominator of 100. 5 60 100 60% 0.4 0.40 40 100 40% In this lesson we will practice another method of changing a fraction to a percent. Since 100% equals 1, we can multiply a fraction by 100% to form an equivalent number. Here we multiply 3 5 by 100%: 5 100% 300% Then we simplify and find that 3 5 equals 60%. 300% 60% We can use the same procedure to change decimals to percents. Here we multiply 0.375 by 100%. Thinking Skill Discuss How can you use mental math to change a decimal to a percent? 0.375 × 100% = 37.5% To change a number to a percent, multiply the number by 100%. L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 1"
"Example 1 Change 1 3 to a percent. Solution We multiply 1 3 by 100%. 3 100% 100% To simplify, we divide 100% by 3 and write the quotient as a mixed number. % 3100% 33 1 Example 2 Write 1.2 as a percent. Solution We multiply 1.2 by 100%. 1.2 × 100% = 120% In some applications a percent may be greater than 100%. If the number we are changing to a percent is greater than 1, then the percent is greater than 100%. Example 3 Write 2 1 4 as a percent. Solution We show two methods below. Method 1: We split the whole number and fraction. The mixed number 2 1 means “2 1 4.” We change each part to a percent and then add. 2 1 200% + 25% = 225% Method 2: We change the mixed number to an improper fraction. The mixed number 2 1 4 equals the improper fraction 9 4. We then change 9 4 to a percent. % 100 % 225"
"Example 4 Write 2 1 6 as a percent. Solution Method 1 shown in example 3 is quick, if we can recall the percent equivalent of a fraction. Method 2 is easier if the percent equivalent does not readily come to mind. We will use method 2 in this example. We write the mixed number 2 1 6 as the improper fraction 13 6 and multiply by 100%. 6 100% 1300% Now we divide 1300% by 6 and write the quotient as a mixed number. 1300% 216 2 3% Example 5 Twenty of the thirty students on the bus were girls. What percent of the students on the bus were girls? Solution We first find the fraction of the students that were girls. Then we convert the fraction to a percent. Girls were 20 30 Qor 2 3R of the students on the bus. Now we multiply the fraction by 100%, which is the percent name for 1. We can use either 20 30 or 2 3, as we show below. 100 % 200% 66 2 3% or 3 100% 200% 66 2 3% We find that % 66 2 of the students on the bus were girls. Practice Set Change each decimal number to a percent by multiplying by 100%: a. 0.5 b. 0.06 c. 0.125 d. 0.45 e. 1.3 f. 0.025 g. 0.09 h. 1.25 i. 0.625 Change each fraction or mixed number to a percent by multiplying by 100%: j. 2 k. 1 l. 1 m. 11 n. 24 o. 11 p. What percent of this rectangle is shaded? q. Connect What percent of a yard is a foot? Saxon Math Course 1"
