"Saxon Math Course 1 22. (Inv. 6) Conclude A pyramid with a square base has how many edges? 23. (71) What is the area of this parallelogram? * 24. (93) Classify The parallelogram in problem 23 is divided into two congruent triangles. Both triangles may be described as which of the following? A acute B right C obtuse 25. (14) During the year, the temperature ranged from −37°F in winter to 103°F in summer. How many degrees was the range of temperature for the year? 26. (Inv. 7, 79) Model The coordinates of the three vertices of a triangle are (0, 0), (0, −4), and (−4, 0). Graph the triangle and find its area. 27. (Inv. 5) Margie’s first nine test scores are shown below. 21, 25, 22, 19, 22, 24, 20, 22, 24 a. What is the mode of these scores? b. What is the median of these scores? * 28. (92) 23  225  3  42  24 29. (78) Sandra filled the aquarium with 24 quarts of water. How many gallons of water did Sandra pour into the aquarium? 30. (58, 74) A bag contains lettered tiles, two for each letter of the alphabet. What is the probability of drawing a tile with the letter A? Express the probability ratio as a fraction and as a decimal rounded to the nearest hundredth. 10 in. 8 in."
"Reducing Rates Before Multiplying Power Up Building Power facts Power Up G mental math a. Number Sense: 60 ∙ 80 b. Number Sense: 437 − 150 c. Percent: 25% of 80 d. Calculation: $3.99 + $4.28 e. Decimals: 17.5 ÷ 100 f. Number Sense: 30 × 55 g. Algebra: If w = 10, what does 7w equal? h. Calculation: 6 × 8, + 1, 2 , × 5, + 1, 2 , × 3, ÷ 2, 2 problem solving Between the prime number 2 and its double, 4, there is a prime number 2 3 4 Is there at least one prime number between every prime number and its double? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Since Lesson 70 we have practiced reducing fractions before multiplying. This is sometimes called canceling. 2 5 1 We can cancel units before multiplying just as we cancel numbers. 4 miles 1 hour 2 hours 8 miles 8 miles Since rates are ratios of two measures, multiplying and dividing rates involves multiplying and dividing units. Example 1 Multiply 55 miles per hour by six hours. L E S S O N"
"Saxon Math Course 1 Solution Math Language Recall that a ratio is a comparison of two numbers by division. We write the rate 55 miles per hour as the ratio 55 miles over 1 hour, because “per” indicates division. We write six hours as the ratio 6 hours over 1. 55 miles 1 hour 6 hours The unit “hour” appears above and below the division line, so we can cancel hours. 55 miles 1 hour 6 hours 330 miles Connect Can you think of a word problem to fit this equation? Example 2 Multiply 5 feet by 12 inches per foot. Solution We write ratios of 5 feet over 1 and 12 inches over 1 foot. We then cancel units and multiply. 5 feet 12 inches 1 foot 60 inches Practice Set When possible, cancel numbers and units before multiplying: a. 3 dollars 1 hour 8 hours b. 6 baskets 10 shots 100 shots Reading Math The abbreviation “kwh” stands for kilowatt hours, a rate used to measure energy. c. 10 cents 1 kwh 26.3 kwh d. 160 km 2 hours 10 hours e. Multiply 18 teachers by 29 students per teacher. f. Multiply 2.3 meters by 100 centimeters per meter. g. Solve this problem by multiplying two ratios: How far will the train travel in 6 hours at 45 miles per hour? Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (41) What is the total price of a $45.79 item when 7% sales tax is added to the price? * 2. (95) Jeff is 1.67 meters tall. How many centimeters tall is Jeff ? (Multiply 1.67 meters by 100 centimeters per meter.) 3. (77) Analyze If 5 8 of the 40 seeds sprouted, how many seeds did not sprout?"
