"Saxon Math Course 1 20. (88) The ratio of children to adults in the theater was 5 to 3. If there were 45 children, how many adults were there? 21. (14, 17) Arrange these numbers in order from least to greatest: 1, 1, 0, 1 2, 1 22. (64) Classify These two triangles together form a quadrilateral with only one pair of parallel sides. What type of quadrilateral is formed? 23. (60) Conclude Do the triangles in this quadrilateral appear to be congruent or not congruent? * 24. (98) a. Analyze What is the measure of ∠A in △ABC? b. Analyze What is the measure of the exterior angle marked x? 25. (33, 74) Write 40% as a a. simplified fraction. b. simplified decimal number. 26. (86) The diameter of this circle is 20 mm. What is the area of the circle? (Use 3.14 for π.) * 27. (92) 23 281 32 a1 2b * 28. (95) Multiply 120 inches by 1 foot per 12 inches. 120 in. 1 ft 12 in. 29. (23, 58) A bag contains 20 red marbles and 15 blue marbles. a. What is the ratio of red marbles to blue marbles? b. If one marble is drawn from the bag, what is the probability that the marble will be blue? * 30. (93) Conclude An architect drew a set of plans for a house. In the plans, the roof is supported by a triangular framework. When the house is built, two sides of the framework will be 19 feet long and the base will be 33 feet long. Classified by side length, what type of triangle will be formed? A C B 40°110° x 20 mm"
"Fraction-Decimal-Percent Equivalents Power Up Building Power facts Power Up K mental math a. Number Sense: 60 ∙ 50 b. Number Sense: 741 − 450 c. Percent: 25% of 48 d. Calculation: $12.99 + $4.75 e. Decimals: 37.5 ÷ 100 f. Number Sense: 30 × 15 g. Measurement: Which is greater 1 liter or 1000 milliliters? h. Calculation: 7 × 7, + 1, ÷ 2, 2 , × 4, − 2, ÷ 3, × 5, + 3, ÷ 3 problem solving If the last page of a section of large newspaper is page 36, what is the fewest number of sheets of paper that could be in that section? New Concept Increasing Knowledge Fractions, decimals, and percents are three ways to express parts of a whole. An important skill is being able to change from one form to another. This lesson asks you to complete tables that show equivalent fractions, decimals, and percents. Example Complete the table. Fraction Decimal Percent a. b. c. 0.3 d. e. f. 40% Solution The numbers in each row should be equivalent. For 1 2 we write a decimal and a percent. For 0.3 we write a fraction and a percent. For 40% we write a fraction and a decimal. a. 1 2 21.0 0.5 b. % 2 100% 50 L E S S O N"
