"Example The diameter of this cylinder is 20 cm. Its height is 10 cm. What is its volume? 10 cm 20 cm Solution To calculate the volume of a cylinder, we find the area of a circular end of the cylinder and multiply that area by the height of the cylinder—the distance between the circular ends. Since the diameter of the cylinder is 20 cm, the radius is 10 cm. A square with a side the length of the radius has an area of 100 cm2. So the area of the circle is about 3.14 times 100 cm2, which is 314 cm2. 20 cm 10 cm 100 cm2 Now we multiply the area of the circular end of the cylinder by the height of the cylinder. 314 cm2 × 10 cm = 3140 cm3 We find that the volume of the cylinder is approximately 3140 cm3. Practice Set A large can of soup has a diameter of about 8 cm and a height of about 12 cm. The volume of the can is about how many cubic centimeters? Round your answer to the nearest hundred cubic centimeters. Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (73) Write the prime factorization of 750 using exponents. 2. (7) Estimate About how long is your little finger? A 0.5 mm B 5 mm C 50 mm D 500 mm 8 cm 12 cm Thinking Skill Explain Why is the volume of this cylinder an approximation and not a precise number?"
